Use an accessor/function in both frameworks so the query is rebuilt when inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";

const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  projectId ? app.todos.where({ projectId }).orderBy("title", "asc") : undefined,
);
```

Solid:
```ts
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: projectId()
    ? app.todos.where({ projectId: projectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc")
    : undefined,
}));
```
Passing a prebuilt query would capture the old input and stop reacting.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two optimistic UI writes that should appear locally together right after the batch commits.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, a, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, b, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when both writes must stay staged until authority accepts them and then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, a, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, b, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Use a real in-memory server and two real clients, not mocks. Insert several rows from client A, await each write with `.wait({ tier: "edge" })`, then on client B use `vi.waitFor` and assert a normalized result instead of raw query order.

```ts
const titles = ["c", "a", "b"];
await Promise.all(
  titles.map((title) => alice.insert(app.todos, { title }).wait({ tier: "edge" }))
);

await vi.waitFor(async () => {
  const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
  expect(rows.map((r) => r.title).sort()).toEqual([...titles].sort());
});
```

If the API supports ordering, request an explicit stable order; otherwise sort by a stable key in the assertion. Avoid fixed sleeps, and shut down both DBs and the server in teardown.

Use `createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect)` and create separate Alice and Bob sessions. Have Alice create the row, then prove Bob cannot read it and cannot mutate it, while Alice still can.

```ts
const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

const row = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Private" }).value;

await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);
bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Nope" }));
bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.todos, row.id));
alice.expectAllowed((db) => db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Updated" }));
```

For read policies, assert absence (`[]`), not an exception. If the policy depends on JWT claims or ownership fields, include those claims in `testApp.as(...)` and test each operation independently.
